<p class="drop-cap">Walk into a Byzantine church and the first thing that commands your attention is the wall. Not the walls of the building. The wall: a screen of icons stretching across the front of the church, separating the nave (where the congregation stands) from the sanctuary (where the altar stands). This is the <strong>iconostasis</strong> — from the Greek <em>eikon</em> (image) and <em>stasis</em> (standing place). A place where images stand.</p>

<p>Visitors from Western traditions sometimes see the iconostasis as a barrier. Something blocking the view. Hiding the action. The Eastern understanding is the opposite. The iconostasis does not hide the sacred. It reveals it. It is a window, not a wall. A theology in wood and paint.</p>

<h2>Origins</h2>

<p>The earliest Christian churches had no iconostasis. The sanctuary was separated from the nave by a low barrier called a <em>templon</em> — waist-high, often made of marble, with columns supporting a beam (<em>epistyle</em>) across the top. You could see the altar. The separation was symbolic, not visual.</p>

<p>Over the centuries, icons began to accumulate on and around the templon. First a few. Then rows. By the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, especially in the Russian tradition, the iconostasis had grown into a towering structure of five or more tiers, filling the entire east wall of the church from floor to ceiling.</p>

<p>The development was organic, not decreed. No council mandated the full iconostasis. It grew from the instincts of worship: if icons are windows into heaven, then multiplying them creates an entire wall of heaven, visible and present.</p>

