<h2>The Royal Doors</h2>

<p>At the center of the iconostasis stand the <strong>Royal Doors</strong> (also called the Holy Doors or Beautiful Gates). These are the double doors through which the priest enters and exits the sanctuary during the liturgy. They are called "royal" because through them comes the King — Christ Himself, in the Eucharist.</p>

<p>The Royal Doors typically bear icons of the four Evangelists (Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John) and the Annunciation (the Archangel Gabriel and the Virgin Mary). The logic: the Gospels are the door through which Christ enters human consciousness, and the Annunciation is the door through which He entered human flesh.</p>

<p>During the Divine Liturgy, the opening and closing of the Royal Doors marks the rhythm of revelation and mystery. When they open, heaven and earth communicate visibly. When they close, the mystery continues behind the veil. The congregation sees and does not see, knows and does not know. This tension is intentional.</p>

<h2>The Bottom Tier: The Local Row</h2>

<p>The lowest tier of icons, at eye level, is the most important for the worshipper. Its arrangement follows a consistent pattern across nearly all Byzantine churches:</p>

<p><strong>To the right of the Royal Doors</strong> (as you face the iconostasis): the icon of <strong>Christ</strong>. Almost always Christ Pantocrator — the "Ruler of All" — holding the Gospels in one hand and blessing with the other. This is His church. He is the first face you see.</p>

<p><strong>To the left of the Royal Doors:</strong> the icon of the <strong>Theotokos</strong> (the Mother of God), usually holding the Christ Child. She points toward Him. Her presence says: God was born. He has a mother. The Incarnation is real.</p>

<p><strong>To the right of Christ:</strong> the icon of <strong>St. John the Baptist</strong>, the Forerunner — the last prophet, the one who prepared the way.</p>

<p><strong>To the left of the Theotokos:</strong> the <strong>patronal icon</strong> — the icon of the saint or feast to whom the church is dedicated. A church named Holy Transfiguration will have the Transfiguration icon here. A church named St. Nicholas will have St. Nicholas.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. John of Damascus, On the Divine Images, 8th century">
  The icon is a hymn of triumph, a manifestation of victory, a monument to the saints — and it illumines those who gaze upon it.
</Pullquote>

<h2>The Upper Tiers</h2>

<p>Above the local row, larger iconostases add additional tiers. The arrangement varies by tradition, but the most common pattern in the Russian and Ukrainian traditions includes:</p>

<p><strong>The Deesis tier:</strong> Christ enthroned at center, flanked by the Theotokos and John the Baptist, who turn toward Him in intercession. Behind them, archangels, apostles, and major saints, all facing Christ. This is the Church praying — a visual representation of the communion of saints.</p>

<p><strong>The Feast tier:</strong> Icons of the twelve great feasts of the liturgical year: Nativity, Theophany, Transfiguration, Crucifixion, Resurrection, Ascension, Pentecost, and others. The cycle of salvation history, compressed into a single row.</p>

<p><strong>The Prophets tier:</strong> Old Testament prophets holding scrolls with their messianic prophecies. Moses, Isaiah, Jeremiah, Elijah. At the center, the icon of the Theotokos of the Sign — Mary with arms raised in prayer, the Christ Child visible in her womb. She is the fulfillment of everything the prophets foretold.</p>

<p><strong>The Patriarchs tier:</strong> The ancestors of the faith: Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Noah. At the very top, sometimes, the icon of the Holy Trinity. The whole history of salvation, from creation to the Second Coming, read from top to bottom.</p>

