<h2>The Side Doors</h2>

<p>Flanking the Royal Doors are two smaller doors, one on each side. These are the <strong>deacon's doors</strong> (or "north" and "south" doors). Through them, deacons, servers, and clergy move in and out of the sanctuary during services. They often bear icons of the Archangels Michael and Gabriel, or of the deacon-saints Stephen and Laurence.</p>

<p>The arrangement of three doors in the iconostasis is sometimes read as trinitarian, sometimes as a reference to the three entrances of the ancient Temple in Jerusalem. Both readings coexist.</p>

<h2>Not a Wall — A Window</h2>

<p>The iconostasis does not separate the congregation from God. It makes visible what is otherwise invisible: the communion of saints, the presence of Christ, the intercession of the Theotokos, the sweep of salvation history from Adam to the Second Coming.</p>

<p>Stand in front of an iconostasis and look. The faces look back. They are not decorations. They are presences. The saints depicted are understood to be genuinely present in the liturgy, praying alongside the congregation. The iconostasis makes that invisible reality visible.</p>

<p>The Royal Doors open. Incense billows out. The priest emerges carrying the Gospel or the Eucharist. For a moment, the boundary between heaven and earth dissolves. Then the doors close again. The mystery continues.</p>

<p>That rhythm — revelation and hiddenness, presence and mystery — is the heartbeat of Byzantine worship. The iconostasis is its visible expression.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>For a theological treatment of icons and their place in worship, see Leonid Ouspensky's <em>Theology of the Icon</em>. Solrunn Nes's <em>The Mystical Language of Icons</em> provides an accessible visual introduction. For the historical development of the iconostasis as an architectural form, see Sharon Gerstel's <em>Beholding the Sacred Mysteries</em>.</p>

